## OpenAPI 3.1 Tool Definitions

Roko tool schemas are JSON Schema Draft 2020-12 compliant, aligning with OpenAPI 3.1.
This means any Roko `ToolDef` can be exported as an OpenAPI operation, and any OpenAPI spec
can be imported as Roko tools. The bridge enables interoperability with Claude's function
calling API (`input_schema`), OpenAI's function calling, and the broader API ecosystem.

### Schema Generation from Rust Types

The `schemars` crate derives JSON Schema from Rust parameter structs at compile time,
closing the loop between Rust types and tool parameter schemas:

```rust
use schemars::JsonSchema;
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

/// Input parameters — schemars derives JSON Schema automatically.
#[derive(Debug, Deserialize, JsonSchema)]
pub struct ReadFileParams {
    /// Absolute path to the file to read.
    pub file_path: String,
    /// Line number to start reading from (1-indexed).
    #[schemars(range(min = 1))]
    pub offset: Option<u32>,
    /// Number of lines to read.
    #[schemars(range(min = 1, max = 10000))]
    pub limit: Option<u32>,
}

/// Generate the JSON Schema at compile time.
pub fn schema() -> serde_json::Value {
    serde_json::to_value(schemars::schema_for!(ReadFileParams)).unwrap()
}
```

This produces a schema compatible with Claude's `input_schema` format:

```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "file_path": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "Absolute path to the file to read."
    },
    "offset": {
      "type": ["integer", "null"],
      "minimum": 1,
      "description": "Line number to start reading from (1-indexed)."
    },
    "limit": {
      "type": ["integer", "null"],
      "minimum": 1,
      "maximum": 10000,
      "description": "Number of lines to read."
    }
  },
  "required": ["file_path"]
}
```

### OpenAPI Import/Export

```rust
/// Convert an OpenAPI 3.1 spec into Roko ToolDefs.
/// Each path+method pair becomes a separate tool.
pub fn import_openapi(spec: &openapiv3::OpenAPI) -> Vec<ToolDef> {
    let mut tools = Vec::new();
    for (path, item) in &spec.paths.paths {
        for (method, operation) in item.iter() {
            let name = operation.operation_id
                .clone()
                .unwrap_or_else(|| format!("{}_{}", method, sanitize_path(path)));
            let description = operation.summary
                .as_deref()
                .or(operation.description.as_deref())
                .unwrap_or("No description");
            let input_schema = extract_request_schema(operation);

            tools.push(ToolDef {
                name: Box::leak(name.into_boxed_str()),
                description: Box::leak(description.to_string().into_boxed_str()),
                category: Category::Custom("openapi".into()),
                capability: match method {
                    "get" | "head" | "options" => CapabilityTier::Read,
                    _ => CapabilityTier::Write,
                },
                risk_tier: RiskTier::Layer2,
                input_schema,
                // ... remaining fields with defaults
            });
        }
    }
    tools
}

/// Export all ToolDefs as an OpenAPI 3.1 spec.
pub fn export_openapi(tools: &[ToolDef], info: OpenApiInfo) -> openapiv3::OpenAPI {
    let mut spec = openapiv3::OpenAPI {
        openapi: "3.1.0".into(),
        info: openapiv3::Info {
            title: info.title,
            version: info.version,
            ..Default::default()
        },
        ..Default::default()
    };
    for tool in tools {
        let path = format!("/tools/{}", tool.name);
        let operation = openapiv3::Operation {
            operation_id: Some(tool.name.to_string()),
            summary: Some(tool.description.to_string()),
            request_body: Some(schema_to_request_body(&tool.input_schema)),
            ..Default::default()
        };
        spec.paths.paths.insert(path, PathItem::post(operation));
    }
    spec
}
```

### Claude/OpenAI Function Calling Compatibility

Roko tool definitions map directly to LLM provider function calling formats:

| Roko Field | Claude API | OpenAI API | MCP |
|---|---|---|---|
| `name` | `name` | `name` | `name` |
| `description` | `description` | `description` | `description` |
| `input_schema` (JSON Schema) | `input_schema` | `parameters` | `inputSchema` |
| `strict: true` | Supported | Supported | N/A |

The conversion is mechanical — no information is lost. Tools defined in Roko work with any
LLM backend that supports function calling.

---

## Tool Versioning

Tools evolve over time. Parameter schemas change, behaviors shift, new capabilities are added.
Tool versioning prevents breaking changes from silently corrupting agent behavior.

### Semantic Versioning for Tools

Every `ToolDef` carries a version following semver:

```rust
/// Extended ToolDef with versioning support.
pub struct VersionedToolDef {
    /// The base tool definition.
    pub def: ToolDef,
    /// Semantic version of this tool.
    pub version: semver::Version,
    /// Deprecation notice (if this version is deprecated).
    pub deprecated: Option<DeprecationNotice>,
    /// Changelog entries for this version.
    pub changelog: &'static [&'static str],
}

pub struct DeprecationNotice {
    /// When this version was deprecated.
    pub since: &'static str,
    /// Replacement tool (if any).
    pub replacement: Option<&'static str>,
    /// When this version will be removed.
    pub removal_target: Option<&'static str>,
    /// Migration instructions.
    pub migration: &'static str,
}
```

### Version Semantics

| Change Type | Version Bump | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| Breaking schema change | **Major** | Remove required param, change param type, alter behavior |
| New optional param | **Minor** | Add `include_metadata: Option<bool>` |
| New output field | **Minor** | Add `created_at` to response |
| Bug fix | **Patch** | Fix edge case, improve error message |
| Description change | **Patch** | Clarify when to use tool |

### Version Resolution

The tool registry supports version constraints for tool selection:

```rust
impl VersionedToolRegistry {
    /// Resolve a tool by name and version constraint.
    /// Returns the highest version matching the constraint.
    pub fn resolve(
        &self,
        name: &str,
        constraint: &semver::VersionReq,
    ) -> Option<&VersionedToolDef> {
        self.tools.get(name)
            .and_then(|versions| {
                versions.iter()
                    .filter(|v| constraint.matches(&v.version))
                    .max_by(|a, b| a.version.cmp(&b.version))
            })
    }

    /// List all versions of a tool.
    pub fn versions(&self, name: &str) -> Vec<&semver::Version> {
        self.tools.get(name)
            .map(|vs| vs.iter().map(|v| &v.version).collect())
            .unwrap_or_default()
    }
}
```

### Configuration

```toml
# roko.toml — pin tool versions per agent
[tools.versions]
"read_file" = ">=1.0.0, <2.0.0"
"web_search" = "^2.1.0"
"github.get_pr" = "~1.3"
```

### Test Criteria

- Version resolution returns the highest matching version for a constraint.
- `^1.0.0` matches `1.0.0`, `1.5.3`, but not `2.0.0`.
- Deprecated tools emit a warning when selected by the agent.
- Major version bump triggers a migration check in CI.

---

## Tool Composition and Dataflow

Tools compose into pipelines — sequential chains, parallel fans, and DAGs. The plan executor
already handles DAG-based task composition. This section specifies how individual tool calls
compose within a single agent turn.

### Composition Patterns

**Sequential (pipe):** Output of tool A feeds input of tool B.

```
read_file → grep → edit_file
```

**Parallel (fan-out):** Multiple independent tools execute concurrently, results merged.

```
┌─ web_search("rust async") ──┐
│                              ├─ merge → compose_answer
└─ web_search("tokio guide") ─┘
```

**Conditional (branch):** Tool selection depends on prior tool output.

```
read_file → if contains("TODO") then grep("TODO") else skip
```

**Iterative (loop):** Tool called repeatedly with refined inputs until condition met.

```
loop { edit_file → run_tests → if pass then break }
```

### ToolPipeline Definition

```rust
/// A composable pipeline of tool invocations.
pub struct ToolPipeline {
    /// Pipeline stages, executed in order.
    pub stages: Vec<PipelineStage>,
    /// Maximum total execution time for the pipeline.
    pub timeout: Duration,
    /// Whether to abort on first failure or continue.
    pub fail_fast: bool,
}

pub enum PipelineStage {
    /// Single tool invocation.
    Single {
        tool: String,
        params: serde_json::Value,
        /// JSONPath expression to extract from prior stage output.
        input_mapping: Option<String>,
    },
    /// Parallel fan-out — all tools execute concurrently.
    Parallel {
        tools: Vec<(String, serde_json::Value)>,
        /// How to merge parallel results.
        merge_strategy: MergeStrategy,
    },
    /// Conditional — select tool based on prior output.
    Conditional {
        condition: String, // JSONPath predicate
        if_true: Box<PipelineStage>,
        if_false: Option<Box<PipelineStage>>,
    },
}

pub enum MergeStrategy {
    /// Collect all results into an array.
    Array,
    /// Merge objects (later results override earlier on key conflict).
    MergeObjects,
    /// Take the first successful result.
    FirstSuccess,
}

impl ToolPipeline {
    /// Execute the pipeline, threading outputs through stages.
    pub async fn execute(
        &self,
        initial_input: serde_json::Value,
        registry: &dyn ToolRegistry,
        ctx: &ToolContext,
    ) -> Result<Vec<ToolResult>> {
        let mut results = Vec::new();
        let mut current_output = initial_input;

        for stage in &self.stages {
            let stage_result = match stage {
                PipelineStage::Single { tool, params, input_mapping } => {
                    let merged_params = if let Some(mapping) = input_mapping {
                        apply_jsonpath_mapping(params, &current_output, mapping)?
                    } else {
                        params.clone()
                    };
                    let tool_def = registry.get(tool)
                        .ok_or_else(|| anyhow!("Tool not found: {tool}"))?;
                    let result = execute_tool(tool_def, merged_params, ctx).await?;
                    current_output = result.data.clone();
                    result
                }
                PipelineStage::Parallel { tools, merge_strategy } => {
                    let futures: Vec<_> = tools.iter().map(|(name, params)| {
                        let tool_def = registry.get(name).unwrap();
                        execute_tool(tool_def, params.clone(), ctx)
                    }).collect();
                    let parallel_results = futures::future::join_all(futures).await;
                    let merged = merge_results(&parallel_results, merge_strategy)?;
                    current_output = merged.data.clone();
                    merged
                }
                PipelineStage::Conditional { condition, if_true, if_false } => {
                    if evaluate_jsonpath_predicate(&current_output, condition)? {
                        execute_stage(if_true, &current_output, registry, ctx).await?
                    } else if let Some(else_stage) = if_false {
                        execute_stage(else_stage, &current_output, registry, ctx).await?
                    } else {
                        ToolResult::read(current_output.clone())
                    }
                }
            };
            results.push(stage_result);
        }
        Ok(results)
    }
}
```

### ReAct-Style Interleaved Composition

The predominant composition pattern in Roko agents is ReAct (Yao et al., 2023): interleaved
reasoning traces and tool actions. The LLM decides at each step which tool to call (or whether
to stop), based on prior observations. This is implemented naturally by the agent's cognitive
loop — the LLM generates tool calls as part of its output, the runtime executes them, and the
results are fed back as observations.

```
Thought: I need to check the current test status.
Action: run_tests { "command": "cargo test --workspace" }
Observation: 3 tests failed — error in router.rs line 42.
Thought: Let me read that file to understand the failure.
Action: read_file { "file_path": "/path/to/router.rs", "offset": 35, "limit": 15 }
Observation: [file contents showing the bug]
Thought: The issue is a missing match arm. Let me fix it.
Action: edit_file { "file_path": "/path/to/router.rs", "old_string": "...", "new_string": "..." }
```

This pattern requires no explicit pipeline definition — the LLM IS the pipeline controller.
The `ToolPipeline` struct above is for programmatic (non-LLM) composition, such as gate
pipelines, automated test sequences, and batch operations.

