## Defense-in-Depth Sandboxing Architecture

The safety system employs defense-in-depth: multiple independent layers that each provide
security guarantees. An attacker must simultaneously breach ALL layers to cause harm.

### Layer Model

```
Layer 1: Capability Tokens (Rust type system)
    Structural guarantee: write tools cannot execute without Capability<T>.
    Breach requires: Rust compiler bug or unsafe block misuse.

Layer 2: Safety Hook Chain (runtime policy)
    Behavioral guarantee: operations violating policy are blocked.
    Breach requires: all 7 hooks passing malicious input.

Layer 3: WASM Sandbox (process isolation)
    Isolation guarantee: untrusted code cannot access host resources.
    Breach requires: Wasmtime/WASI vulnerability + sandbox escape.

Layer 4: Process Isolation (MCP transport)
    OS-level guarantee: MCP servers run in separate processes.
    Breach requires: IPC exploit + privilege escalation.
```

### Capability-Based Security (Capsicum Pattern)

The tool permission model follows the Capsicum capability-based security pattern (Watson
et al., USENIX Security 2010): tools operate under the **principle of least privilege**,
receiving only the capabilities they need. No ambient authority — a tool cannot discover
resources it was not explicitly granted access to.

```rust
/// Tool permission manifest — declares the minimum capabilities a tool needs.
/// Follows the Capsicum principle: no ambient authority, explicit grants only.
pub struct ToolPermissionManifest {
    /// Filesystem paths this tool can read.
    pub read_paths: Vec<PathBuf>,
    /// Filesystem paths this tool can write.
    pub write_paths: Vec<PathBuf>,
    /// Network hosts this tool can contact.
    pub allowed_hosts: Vec<String>,
    /// Maximum execution time.
    pub timeout: Duration,
    /// Maximum memory usage.
    pub max_memory_bytes: u64,
    /// Whether this tool can invoke other tools (chain calls).
    pub can_chain: bool,
    /// Safety classification.
    pub risk_level: ToolRiskLevel,
    /// Minimum required trust level to execute this tool.
    pub min_trust: TrustLevel,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum ToolRiskLevel {
    /// No side effects. Safe to retry, safe to speculate.
    ReadOnly,
    /// Creates state. Needs idempotency checks.
    SideEffect,
    /// Deletes or overwrites. Needs confirmation gate.
    Destructive,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, PartialOrd, Ord)]
pub enum TrustLevel {
    /// Built-in tools compiled with roko.
    Builtin,
    /// Domain plugin tools compiled as workspace crates.
    DomainPlugin,
    /// Runtime-loaded shared library plugins.
    RuntimePlugin,
    /// MCP server tools (separate process).
    McpTool,
    /// WASM sandboxed tools (strictest isolation).
    WasmSandboxed,
    /// Unverified third-party tools.
    Untrusted,
}
```

### Permission Enforcement

```rust
/// Enforce permission manifest before tool execution.
pub async fn enforce_permissions(
    tool: &ToolDef,
    manifest: &ToolPermissionManifest,
    params: &serde_json::Value,
    ctx: &ToolContext,
) -> Result<()> {
    // Check filesystem access
    if let Some(path) = extract_path_param(params) {
        let path = PathBuf::from(path);
        let can_read = manifest.read_paths.iter().any(|p| path.starts_with(p));
        let can_write = manifest.write_paths.iter().any(|p| path.starts_with(p));

        if tool.capability == CapabilityTier::Write && !can_write {
            return Err(anyhow!(
                "Tool {} denied write access to {}: not in write_paths",
                tool.name, path.display()
            ));
        }
        if !can_read && !can_write {
            return Err(anyhow!(
                "Tool {} denied access to {}: not in read_paths or write_paths",
                tool.name, path.display()
            ));
        }
    }

    // Check network access
    if let Some(host) = extract_host_param(params) {
        if !manifest.allowed_hosts.iter().any(|h| host.ends_with(h)) {
            return Err(anyhow!(
                "Tool {} denied network access to {}: not in allowed_hosts",
                tool.name, host
            ));
        }
    }

    // Check trust level
    let tool_trust = ctx.trust_level_for(tool);
    if tool_trust < manifest.min_trust {
        return Err(anyhow!(
            "Tool {} requires trust level {:?} but has {:?}",
            tool.name, manifest.min_trust, tool_trust
        ));
    }

    Ok(())
}
```

### Post-Facto Validation (GoEx Pattern)

Inspired by GoEx (Patil et al., UC Berkeley, 2024), destructive tool operations support
post-facto validation with undo capabilities:

```rust
/// Reversible tool execution with damage confinement.
pub struct ReversibleExecution {
    /// Snapshot of state before execution.
    pub pre_state: StateSnapshot,
    /// The tool result.
    pub result: ToolResult,
    /// Undo function (if the tool supports reversal).
    pub undo: Option<Box<dyn FnOnce() -> BoxFuture<'static, Result<()>>>>,
    /// Time window for undo (after which changes are committed).
    pub undo_window: Duration,
}

impl ReversibleExecution {
    /// Revert the tool's effects if possible.
    pub async fn rollback(self) -> Result<()> {
        if let Some(undo) = self.undo {
            undo().await?;
            Ok(())
        } else {
            Err(anyhow!("Tool does not support reversal"))
        }
    }
}
```

For chain domain tools, undo is implemented via Revm fork state — the simulation fork is
kept alive for the undo window, and if rollback is requested, the on-chain state change is
not submitted. For file operations, undo is implemented via the backup file created before
edit.

### Configuration

```toml
[tools.safety]
# Defense-in-depth layer control
enable_capability_tokens = true    # Layer 1 (compile-time, cannot disable)
enable_safety_hooks = true         # Layer 2
enable_wasm_sandbox = true         # Layer 3
enable_process_isolation = true    # Layer 4

# Permission manifest defaults
default_timeout_secs = 30
default_max_memory_mb = 256
default_fuel_limit = 10_000_000

# Post-facto validation
undo_window_secs = 60              # Time to rollback destructive ops
snapshot_destructive_ops = true    # Pre-snapshot state for undo
```

### Test Criteria

- Permission enforcement blocks file access outside declared paths.
- Permission enforcement blocks network access to undeclared hosts.
- Trust level check prevents untrusted tools from executing privileged operations.
- ReversibleExecution rollback restores pre-execution state for file operations.
- WASM plugin with no permissions cannot access any filesystem or network resources.
- All four defense layers are independently testable.
- Audit records capture permission violations with full context.

